Warum lieben Programmierer JSON?

Es bildet direkt auf native Datentypen ab.

  • Number
  • String
  • Boolean
  • Array (oder List)
  • Object (oder Dictionary)
  • null

Datenstrukturen von XML

data Node = Text
          | Element Name (Map Name Text) [Node]
  
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<root-element>
  Hello World!

  <kind-element attribut1="foo" 
                attribut2="bar"
                attribut3="baz"/>
  <kind-element>
    <kind-element/>
    <kind-element/>
    <kind-element/>
  </kind-element>
</root-element>

XML Parser

DOM
Document Object Model
SAX
Simple API for XML
SAX DOM
data Event
	= EventBeginDocument
	| EventEndDocument
	| EventBeginDoctype Text (Maybe ExternalID)
	| EventEndDoctype
	| EventInstruction Instruction
	| EventBeginElement Name [(Name, [Content])]
	| EventEndElement Name
	| EventContent Content
	| EventComment Text
	| EventCDATA Text

Datenmodell

Feeds enthalten mehrere Entries

Feeds haben Metadaten

Entries haben Metadaten

RSS 2.0

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<rss version="2.0">
  <channel>
    <title>RSS Title</title>
    <description>This is an example of an RSS feed</description>
    <link>http://www.someexamplerssdomain.com/main.html</link>
    <lastBuildDate>Mon, 06 Sep 2010 00:01:00 +0000 </lastBuildDate>
    <pubDate>Mon, 06 Sep 2009 16:45:00 +0000 </pubDate>
    <ttl>1800</ttl>
 
    <item>
      <title>Example entry</title>
      <description>
        Here is some text containing an interesting description.
      </description>
      <link>http://www.wikipedia.org/</link>
      <guid>unique string per item</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 06 Sep 2009 16:45:00 +0000 </pubDate>
    </item>
 
  </channel>
</rss>

Atom

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom">
  
  <title>Example Feed</title>
  <subtitle>A subtitle.</subtitle>
  <link href="http://example.org/feed/" rel="self" />
  <link href="http://example.org/" />
  <id>urn:uuid:60a76c80-d399-11d9-b91C-0003939e0af6</id>
  <updated>2003-12-13T18:30:02Z</updated>
  
  
  <entry>
    <title>Atom-Powered Robots Run Amok</title>
    <link href="http://example.org/2003/12/13/atom03" />
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://example.org/2003/12/13/atom03.html"/>
    <link rel="edit" href="http://example.org/2003/12/13/atom03/edit"/>
    <id>urn:uuid:1225c695-cfb8-4ebb-aaaa-80da344efa6a</id>
    <updated>2003-12-13T18:30:02Z</updated>
    <summary>Some text.</summary>
    <author>
      <name>John Doe</name>
      <email>johndoe@example.com</email>
    </author>
  </entry>
  
</feed>

ATOM types (1/2)

Nur Text:

<description type="text">I &lt;3 Atom</description>

Escaped HTML:

<description type="html">&lt;b&gt;Atom&lt;/b&gt;-powered!</description>

Richtiges XML:

      <content type="xhtml">
        <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
	  <img src="atom.png"/>
	</div>
      </content>

ATOM types (2/2)

Das @type-Attribut ist fr viele Elemente erlaubt: 

    <title type="html">
      The entry that pwns!
      &lt;script&gt;alert("In your aggregator's face!")&lt;/script&gt;
    </title>

Feed Parsing in der Praxis

Postel's Law (1/5)

Oder: Robustness Principle

  • Be conservative in what you do, be liberal in what you accept from others
  • Be conservative in what you send, liberal in what you accept

Postel's Law (2/5): Kaputtes XML

<title>
  Dick & Doof haben jetzt einen Feed!
</title>
<rss>
  <title>fnord/title>
  <pubDate>2012-12-21T21:42:23Z</pubDate>
  • Auch fr XML einen HTML-Parser (Tagsoup) verwenden
  • Lieber einen SAX- statt DOM-Parser verwenden

Postel's Law (3/5): Im XML

  • Wie in HTML-Dokumenten knnen auch Feeds relative Links enthalten
  • HTML-Content sollte ebenfalls geparst werden

Postel's Law (4/5): Charsets

  • Verschiedene Charsets in einem XML-Dokument?
  • Mglich.

Postel's Law (5/5): HTTP Server

  • Verschiedene Arten von Redirects werden hufig genutzt
  • Content-Encoding: deflate, gzip
  • HTTPS

HTTP Not Modified

Regelmiges Polling: Gibts was neues?

$ curl -I http://www.c3d2.de/news-rss.xml
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: application/xml
Accept-Ranges: bytes
ETag: "927778783"
Last-Modified: Tue, 11 Dec 2012 16:57:02 GMT
Content-Length: 161169
Date: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 00:03:37 GMT
Server: lighttpd/1.4.28

Feeds knnen mehr als hundert KB gro werden

$ curl -I \
    -H 'If-None-Match: "927778783"' \
    -H 'If-Modified-Since: Tue, 11 Dec 2012 16:57:02 GMT' \
    http://www.c3d2.de/news-rss.xml
HTTP/1.1 304 Not Modified
[...]

Erweiterungen

Semantik fr Social Media: Activity Streams

  • Konstrukt per Eintrag:
    Somebody [actor] posted [verb] something [object] somewhen [time] to a profile [target].
  • verb: add, delete, favorite, unfavorite, follow, stop-following, ignore, invite, join, leave, like, unlike, save, share, tag, update, ...
  • object types: article, bookmark, comment, event, file, group, image, note, person, place, product, question, ...
  • Location
  • Mood (Plain text & Image)
  • Rating zwischen 1.0 und 5.0
  • Source
  • activitystrea.ms

Activity Streams: Beispiel

<entry xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"
       xmlns:activity="http://activitystrea.ms/spec/1.0/">
  <id>tag:photopanic.example.com,2009:activity/4859/4352</id>
  <title>Geraldine posted a Photo on PhotoPanic</title>
  <published>2009-11-02T15:29:00Z</published>
  <link rel="alternate" type="text/html"
      href="http://example.com/geraldine/activities/4352" />
  <activity:verb>post</activity:verb>
  <activity:object>
    <id>tag:photopanic.example.com,2009:photo/4352</id>
    <activity:object-type>photo</activity:object-type>
  </activity:object>
  <content type="html">
    &lt;p&gt;Geraldine posted a Photo on PhotoPanic&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;img src="/geraldine/photos/4352.jpg"&gt;
  </content>
</entry>

The Real-time Web

RSSCloud (gegenber PuSH)

<cloud domain="rpc.sys.com" port="80"
       path="/RPC2" protocol="xml-rpc"
       registerProcedure="myCloud.rssPleaseNotify"/>
  • Lediglich: "etwas hat sich gendert", keine Inhalte
  • Callback-URL muss auf abonnierendem Host liegen
  • Abonnement hlt 25h, Auffrischen vonnten
  • Von Dave Winer, soll einfacher zu implementieren sein

PubSubHubbub

<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom">
  <link rel="hub"
        href="https://myhub.example.com/endpoint"/>
  ...
</feed>

POST /endpoint

  • subscribe/unsubscribe
  • topic
  • callback URL
  • verify token
  • challenge
  • secret

Salmon

Personalized successor to Trackback/Pingback

<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom">
  <link rel="salmon"
        href="http://example.org/all-replies-endpoint"/>
  <entry
    <link rel="salmon"
          href="http://example.org/repliy-endpoint/2342"/>
<XRD xmlns="http://docs.oasis-open.org/ns/xri/xrd-1.0">
  <Subject>acct:bob@example.com</Subject>
  <Link rel="salmon"
        href="https://example.com/mention-handler"/>
</XRD>

POST /mention-handler
